        function onChartAssetLoad(configs) {
  createChart(configs);
  window.removeEventListener("YFINCHART_SRC_LOAD", onChartAssetLoad);
};
        function getChartConfig(configs) {
  const {
    chartTypeOverride = "",
    chartRange,
    quoteType,
    exchange,
    lang,
    region,
    shouldUseUpdatedBeacon,
    storedChartType,
    studies,
    theme,
    featureFlags
  } = configs;
  const extendedHours = hasExtendedHours(quoteType, exchange);
  const { extendedHoursEnabled } = initialChartSettings();
  const chartType = chartTypeOverride ? chartTypeOverride : storedChartType;
  return {
    chartRange: chartRange || INITIAL_SPAN,
    container: document.querySelector(".chartContainer"),
    disableGridLines: {
      x: true
    },
    enableEventsQuote: false,
    featureFlags,
    layout: {
      chartType,
      extended: extendedHours ? extendedHoursEnabled : false,
      padding: 20
    },
    quoteFeed: {
      lang,
      region
    },
    shouldUseUpdatedBeacon,
    showExtededHours: extendedHours ? extendedHoursEnabled : false,
    studies,
    theme: theme || "light",
    onRapidEvent
  };
};
        function createChart(configs) {
  if (!window.finQuoteChart) {
    toggleOverlay(true);
    const chartConfig = getChartConfig(configs);
    window.finQuoteChart = new window.YFinChart.QuoteChart({
      ...chartConfig
    });
    loadChart(configs);
  }
};
        function loadChart(configs) {
  let quoteChartLoad = void 0;
  let quoteChartRender = void 0;
  const {
    chartRange,
    quoteType,
    symbol,
    loadQuoteCB,
    comparisonSymbol,
    periodicties,
    spans,
    beaconPerf,
    enableQSPChartToolbarCleanup,
    storedShowKeyEvent,
    storedAnalystRatingsKeyEvent,
    storedEconomicEventsKeyEvent,
    storedEarningsKeyEvent
  } = configs;
  if (window.finQuoteChart) {
    const span = chartRange || getInitialSpan(quoteType);
    const interval = getInitialInterval(span);
    window.finQuoteChart.loadChart(
      symbol,
      {
        interval: periodicties[interval],
        span: spans[span]
      },
      (err, stx) => {
        if (err) {
          console.error(err);
          return;
        }
        restoreChartSettings();
        toggleOverlay(false);
        quoteChartRender = Date.now();
        const startTime = window?.finNeoPageStart;
        if (quoteChartLoad && quoteChartRender && startTime) {
          const func = new Function(`return ${beaconPerf}`)();
          func({
            "fin-qsp-chart-load": quoteChartLoad - startTime,
            "fin-qsp-chart-render": quoteChartRender - startTime
          });
        }
        window.chartHasData = stx.chart.dataSegment.length > 0;
        if (loadQuoteCB) {
          const cb = new Function(`return ${loadQuoteCB}`)();
          cb(comparisonSymbol.symbol);
        }
        const showEvent = enableQSPChartToolbarCleanup ? storedEarningsKeyEvent : storedShowKeyEvent;
        const additionalEvent = enableQSPChartToolbarCleanup ? storedAnalystRatingsKeyEvent : storedShowKeyEvent;
        const showEconomicEvents = enableQSPChartToolbarCleanup ? storedEconomicEventsKeyEvent : storedShowKeyEvent;
        window.finQuoteChart.showEventsQuote(
          showEvent,
          additionalEvent,
          showEconomicEvents
        );
      }
    );
    quoteChartLoad = Date.now();
  }
};
        function isMobileChart(width) {
  return width <= CHART_1D_MAX_WIDTH;
};
        function getInitialSpan(quoteType) {
  const isMobile = isMobileChart(window.finQuoteChart.stx.chart.canvasWidth);
  if (["MUTUALFUND", "CUL_IDX", "CUL_SUB_IDX"].indexOf(quoteType) > -1) {
    return isMobile ? "1m-sm" : "1m";
  }
  return isMobile ? INITIAL_SPAN_SM : INITIAL_SPAN;
};
        function getInitialInterval(span) {
  const isMobile = isMobileChart(window.finQuoteChart.stx.chart.canvasWidth);
  if (span === "1mo") {
    return isMobile ? "12h" : "1d";
  }
  return isMobile ? "5m" : "1m";
};
        function setChartSetting(settingName, value) {
  switch (settingName) {
    case "tooltipEnabled":
      window.finQuoteChart.stx.layout.headsUp = { floating: value };
      break;
    case "extendedHoursEnabled":
      window.finQuoteChart.setExtendedHours(value);
      break;
  }
};
        function getLSChartSettings() {
  const defaultSettings = {
    extendedHoursEnabled: true,
    tooltipEnabled: true
  };
  try {
    const lsSettings = window.localStorage.getItem(LS_SETTINGS_KEY);
    if (lsSettings === null) {
      return defaultSettings;
    }
    return JSON.parse(lsSettings);
  } catch (err) {
  }
  return defaultSettings;
};
        function toggleOverlay(shouldShow) {
  const overlay = document.getElementsByClassName("loadingOverlay")[0];
  if (overlay) {
    const value = shouldShow ? "flex" : "none";
    overlay.style.display = value;
  }
}        
        function initialChartSettings() {
  const lsSettings = getLSChartSettings();
  try {
    window.localStorage.setItem(LS_SETTINGS_KEY, JSON.stringify(lsSettings));
  } catch (e) {
  }
  return lsSettings;
}
        function hasExtendedHours(quoteType, exchange) {
  return ["EQUITY", "ETF"].indexOf(quoteType.toUpperCase()) > -1 && ["ASE", "NAS", "NXX", "NMS", "NYQ", "NYS", "PCX", "NCM", "NGM", "BTS"].indexOf(
    exchange.toUpperCase()
  ) > -1;
}
        function restoreChartSettings() {
  const lsSettings = getLSChartSettings();
  setChartSetting("tooltipEnabled", lsSettings.tooltipEnabled);
}
        function onRapidEvent(event) {
  const beacon = window.rapidInstance?.beaconClick;
  const sec = "qsp-chart-keyevent";
  switch (event) {
    case "eventsQuote-clickRight":
      beacon(sec, "next", 0, { itc: 1, elm: "arrow" });
      break;
    case "eventsQuote-clickLeft":
      beacon(sec, "prev", 0, { itc: 1, elm: "arrow" });
      break;
    case "eventsQuote-hover":
      beacon(sec, "key-event", 0, { itc: 2, elm: "event" });
      break;
  }
}
        const initializeChart = function initializeChart(configs) {
  if (!window.finQuoteChart && window.YFinChart?.QuoteChart) {
    onChartAssetLoad(configs);
  } else {
    window.addEventListener("YFINCHART_SRC_LOAD", () => {
      onChartAssetLoad(configs);
    });
  }
};
        const INITIAL_SPAN = '1d-qsp';
        const INITIAL_SPAN_SM = '1d-sm';
        const CHART_1D_MAX_WIDTH = '480';
        const LS_SETTINGS_KEY = 'yf-quote-chart-settings';

yf-1cyto5g">Founded in 2012, Grab provides ride-sharing services, food and grocery delivery, and financial services (payments, consumer loans, and enterprise offerings) in eight Southeast-Asian countries through its mobile platform. The company partners with merchants and riders, connecting them with consumers while charging commission to both sides. Grab has a leading market share in and derives 89% of its revenue from its core businesses, ride-sharing and food delivery. Singapore and Malaysia contributed 58% of revenue as of end-2021. Grab’s main competitors in Southeast Asia are Foodpanda and Gojek, the ride-sharing arm of GoTo. Its financial services business is still in its nascent stage and provides minimal revenue currently. yf-1sxfjua">What's happening with the AI trade?</h3> <p class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">The AI trade powered stocks late last year and into 2024. It started to stumble in the summer as investors questioned when companies were going to start seeing returns on their massive AI investments. But over the last month or so, those AI stocks have started to rise again. href="https://finance.yahoo.com/video/hp-stock-downgraded-bank-america-202816065.html" aria-label="HP stock downgraded at Bank of America" title="HP stock downgraded at Bank of America"><h3 class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">HP stock downgraded at Bank of America</h3> <p class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">HP Inc. (HPQ) shares were trading slightly lower on Friday. Bank of America Securities downgraded the stock to Neutral from Buy. Analyst Wamsi Mohan thinks that potential gains in the PC business will be offset by lower margins in the printing business. Market Domination Anchors Josh Lipton and Julie Hyman discuss the call in the video above. This post was written by Stephanie Mikulich.</p>  </a> <div class="footer yf-1sxfjua">   <div class="publishing yf-1weyqlp">Yahoo Finance Video <i aria-hidden="true" data-svelte-h="svelte-sg6bkb">•</i> 15 hours ago</div> <div class="taxonomy-links yf-13tszyc"><a data-testid="ticker-container" class="ticker x-small    hover2   border  streaming   yf-1jpysdn" aria-label="HPQ" data-ylk="elm:qte;elmt:link;itc:0;sec:sector-news;slk:HPQ;subsec:all;cpos:3" href="/quote/HPQ/" title="HPQ"> <div class="name yf-1jpysdn"> <span class="symbol yf-1jpysdn">HPQ</span> </div> <fin-streamer class="percentChange yf-1jpysdn" data-symbol="HPQ" data-field="regularMarketChangePercent" data-trend="txt" data-pricehint="2" data-tstyle="default" active><span class="txt-negative yf-1jpysdn">-3.91%</span></fin-streamer> </a> </div></div></div> </section>  </li>      <li class="stream-item  yf-ovk92u"> <section class="container sz-x-large stream  yf-1sxfjua responsive" data-testid="storyitem" role="article"> <div class="content yf-1sxfjua"><a class="subtle-link fin-size-small titles noUnderline   yf-1e4diqp" data-ylk="elm:hdln;elmt:link;itc:0;ct:story;slk:Amazon%20dodges%20antitrust%20scrutiny%20in%20UK%20over%20Anthropic%20investment;sec:sector-news;subsec:all;cpos:4;g:337c17e9-8dfc-353d-9dff-61ec83ab3d43" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/news/amazon-dodges-antitrust-scrutiny-uk-143356511.html" aria-label="Amazon dodges antitrust scrutiny in UK over Anthropic investment" title="Amazon dodges antitrust scrutiny in UK over Anthropic investment"><h3 class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">Amazon dodges antitrust scrutiny in UK over Anthropic investment</h3> <p class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">The U.K.s' antitrust authority has concluded that Amazon's partnership and equity investment in AI startup Anthropic can't be investigated under current merger rules due to the size and scope of the deal. The U.K. Competition and Markets Authority's (CMA) announcement comes six months to the day after news emerged that Amazon had completed a $4 billion investment in Anthropic, one of several heavily funded AI-focused startups. The three-year-old firm develops large language models (LLMs) and an</p>  </a> <div class="footer yf-1sxfjua">   <div class="publishing yf-1weyqlp">TechCrunch <i aria-hidden="true" data-svelte-h="svelte-sg6bkb">•</i> 18 hours ago</div> <div class="taxonomy-links yf-13tszyc"><a data-testid="ticker-container" class="ticker x-small    hover2   border  streaming   yf-1jpysdn" aria-label="GOOG" data-ylk="elm:qte;elmt:link;itc:0;sec:sector-news;slk:GOOG;subsec:all;cpos:4" href="/quote/GOOG/" title="GOOG"> <div class="name yf-1jpysdn"> <span class="symbol yf-1jpysdn">GOOG</span> </div> <fin-streamer class="percentChange yf-1jpysdn" data-symbol="GOOG" data-field="regularMarketChangePercent" data-trend="txt" data-pricehint="2" data-tstyle="default" active><span class="txt-positive yf-1jpysdn">+0.89%</span></fin-streamer> </a><a data-testid="ticker-container" class="ticker x-small    hover2   border  streaming   yf-1jpysdn" aria-label="MSFT" data-ylk="elm:qte;elmt:link;itc:0;sec:sector-news;slk:MSFT;subsec:all;cpos:4" href="/quote/MSFT/" title="MSFT"> <div class="name yf-1jpysdn"> <span class="symbol yf-1jpysdn">MSFT</span> </div> <fin-streamer class="percentChange yf-1jpysdn" data-symbol="MSFT" data-field="regularMarketChangePercent" data-trend="txt" data-pricehint="2" data-tstyle="default" active><span class="txt-negative yf-1jpysdn">-0.76%</span></fin-streamer> </a> </div></div></div> </section>  </li>      <li class="stream-item  yf-ovk92u"> <section class="container sz-x-large stream  yf-1sxfjua responsive" data-testid="storyitem" role="article"><a class="subtle-link fin-size-small thumb     yf-1e4diqp" data-ylk="elm:img;elmt:link;itc:0;ct:video;slk:How%20the%20VC%20world%20is%20viewing%20AI;sec:sector-news;subsec:all;cpos:5;g:f26e73d7-c5ac-3458-994c-32389098de01" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/video/vc-world-viewing-ai-153348818.html" aria-label="How the VC world is viewing AI" title="How the VC world is viewing AI"><div style="display: contents; --border-radius:var(--border-radius-m); --aspect-ratio:4/3;"> <img class="tw-bg-opacity-25  yf-13q9uv1" alt="How the VC world is viewing AI" src="https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/ZQtH12RlGBt.7Jbo6FlPzg--~B/Zmk9c3RyaW07aD0xMjY7cT04MDt3PTE2ODthcHBpZD15dGFjaHlvbg--/https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2024-09/f851b230-7c56-11ef-b573-a8dbc8db7e2b.cf.webp" srcset="https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/GMzGIMXVvDJO.kt9acesAg--~B/Zmk9c3RyaW07aD0yNTI7cT04MDt3PTMzNjthcHBpZD15dGFjaHlvbg--/https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2024-09/f851b230-7c56-11ef-b573-a8dbc8db7e2b.cf.webp 2x" fetchpriority="auto" loading="lazy"></div>    </a> <div class="content yf-1sxfjua"><a class="subtle-link fin-size-small titles noUnderline   yf-1e4diqp" data-ylk="elm:hdln;elmt:link;itc:0;ct:video;slk:How%20the%20VC%20world%20is%20viewing%20AI;sec:sector-news;subsec:all;cpos:5;g:f26e73d7-c5ac-3458-994c-32389098de01" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/video/vc-world-viewing-ai-153348818.html" aria-label="How the VC world is viewing AI" title="How the VC world is viewing AI"><h3 class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">How the VC world is viewing AI</h3> <p class="clamp  yf-1sxfjua">ChatGPT maker OpenAI is reportedly shifting from its nonprofit structure to a more traditional for-profit approach. Torch Capital founder and managing partner Jon Keidan sits down with Asking for a Trend Host, Josh Lipton, to explain why the company may be making this change now and check in on competition within the artificial intelligence (AI) space. Keidan tells Yahoo Finance, “As the competition has gotten more severe, OpenAI has shown a lot of success. They've developed product after product released successfully, and I think they're just trying to equalize the playing field. I think they probably felt being a nonprofit was a bit of a weight on them, so they're restructuring to be more competitive with Anthropic or xAI.” The for-profit shift would likely mean the OpenAI CEO Sam Altman would have equity in the company. As far as investing in an AI winner, Keidan says, “We're just still early. And so it's very hard to see what are the competitive advantages and what are going to be the key things that make the winners. And so from that perspective, OpenAI is doing a phenomenal job, but it still remains to be seen across the board. And with Microsoft (MSFT) and Google having other bases of operations that they can play from, [it could] potentially be a challenge.” Keidan says that, as a venture investor, he’s probably more excited about AI than he was a year ago. “The capabilities and the adoption are through the roof, and it's going to absolutely be a moment much like in the 2010s when we saw mobile, social, cloud, and location converge. And that created the DoorDashes (DASH) and Ubers (UBER) and Airbnbs (ABNB).” “The potential is tremendous. I'm more excited than ever. In terms of where it's being hashed out now with these huge companies, infrastructure very early in the curve,” but Keidan says “We're trying to stay out of that, and we're really looking for the commercial application layers, early stage investors and I still think it's early. And on the consumer side, it hasn't been proven out yet, but it will be.” He adds that AI is already improving efficiency within Torch Capital’s start-ups. Keidan notes that he doesn’t expect to see private AI companies announcing initial public offerings anytime soon. “These companies have raised a lot of money. They don't want to be distracted by an IPO. And they're building, and they're growing. I think they're going to sit out another year or maybe two until the markets are wide open. Why create friction when they don't need to?” For more expert insight and the latest market action, click here to watch this full episode of Asking for a Trend. This post was written by Naomi Buchanan.</p>  </a> <div class="footer yf-1sxfjua">   <div class="publishing yf-1weyqlp">Yahoo Finance Video <i aria-hidden="true" data-svelte-h="svelte-sg6bkb">•</i> 20 hours ago</div> <div class="taxonomy-links yf-13tszyc"><a data-testid="ticker-container" class="ticker x-small    hover2   border  streaming   yf-1jpysdn" aria-label="MSFT" data-ylk="elm:qte;elmt:link;itc:0;sec:sector-news;slk:MSFT;subsec:all;cpos:5" href="/quote/MSFT/" title="MSFT"> <div class="name yf-1jpysdn"> <span class="symbol yf-1jpysdn">MSFT</span> </div> <fin-streamer class="percentChange yf-1jpysdn" data-symbol="MSFT" data-field="regularMarketChangePercent" data-trend="txt" data-pricehint="2" data-tstyle="default" active><span class="txt-negative yf-1jpysdn">-0.76%</span></fin-streamer> </a> </div></div></div> </section>  </li>      <li class="stream-item  yf-ovk92u"> <section class="container sz-x-large stream  yf-1sxfjua responsive" data-testid="storyitem" role="article"><a class="subtle-link fin-size-small thumb     yf-1e4diqp" data-ylk="elm:img;elmt:link;itc:0;ct:video;slk:DirecTV%2C%20Dish%20reportedly%20close%20to%20merger%20deal%3A%20BBG;sec:sector-news;subsec:all;cpos:6;g:92deb609-cf1a-3c16-a5f5-d9ca086610a7" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/video/directv-dish-reportedly-close-merger-140015281.html" aria-label="DirecTV, Dish reportedly close to merger deal: BBG" title="DirecTV, Dish reportedly close to merger deal: BBG"><div style="display: contents; firm’s price target on Dynatrace to $64 from $55 and keeps a Buy rating on the shares. While FY24 was slightly worse, this makes for a slightly easier comp in FY25, the firm added. Morningstar categories help investors and investment professionals make meaningful comparisons between funds. The categories make it easier to build well-diversified portfolios, assess potential risk, and identify top-performing funds. We place funds in a given category based on their portfolio statistics and compositions over the past three years. If the fund is new and has no portfolio history, we estimate where it will fall before giving it a more permanent category assignment. They've developed product after product released successfully, and I think they're just trying to equalize the playing field. I think they probably felt being a nonprofit was a bit of a weight on them, so they're restructuring to be more competitive with Anthropic or xAI.” The for-profit shift would likely mean the OpenAI CEO Sam Altman would have equity in the company.\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>As far as investing in an AI winner, Keidan says, “We're just still early. And so it's very hard to see what are the competitive advantages and what are going to be the key things that make the winners. And so from that perspective, OpenAI is doing a phenomenal job, but it still remains to be seen across the board. And with Microsoft (\u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:3;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/MSFT\\\">MSFT\u003C/a>) and Google having other bases of operations that they can play from, [it could] potentially be a challenge.”\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>Keidan says that, as a venture investor, he’s probably more excited about AI than he was a year ago. “The capabilities and the adoption are through the roof, and it's going to absolutely be a moment much like in the 2010s when we saw mobile, social, cloud, and location converge. And that created the DoorDashes (\u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:4;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/DASH\\\">DASH\u003C/a>) and Ubers (\u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:5;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/UBER\\\">UBER\u003C/a>) and Airbnbs (\u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:6;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/ABNB\\\">ABNB\u003C/a>).”\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>“The potential is tremendous. I'm more excited than ever. In terms of where it's being hashed out now with these huge companies, infrastructure very early in the curve,” but Keidan says “We're trying to stay out of that, and we're really looking for the commercial application layers, early stage investors and I still think it's early. And on the consumer side, it hasn't been proven out yet, but it will be.” He adds that AI is already improving efficiency within Torch Capital’s start-ups.\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>Keidan notes that he doesn’t expect to see private AI companies announcing initial public offerings anytime soon. “These companies have raised a lot of money. They don't want to be distracted by an IPO. And they're building, and they're growing. I think they're going to sit out another year or maybe two until the markets are wide open. Why create friction when they don't need to?”\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>For more expert insight and the latest market action, click \u003Ca data-i13n=\\\"cpos:7;pos:1\\\" href=\\\"https://finance.yahoo.com/video/super-micro-stock-tumbles-costco-172424968.html\\\">here\u003C/a> to watch this full episode of Asking for a Trend.\u003C/p>\\n\u003Cp>\u003Cem>This post was written by Naomi Buchanan.\u003C/em>\u003C/p>\",\"summary\":\"ChatGPT maker OpenAI is reportedly shifting from its nonprofit structure to a more traditional for-profit approach. Torch Capital founder and managing partner Jon Keidan sits down with Asking for a Trend Host, Josh Lipton, to explain why the company may be making this change now and check in on competition within the artificial intelligence (AI) space. Keidan tells Yahoo Finance, “As the competition has gotten more severe, OpenAI has shown a lot of success. They've developed product after product released successfully, and I think they're just trying to equalize the playing field. I think they probably felt being a nonprofit was a bit of a weight on them, so they're restructuring to be more competitive with Anthropic or xAI.” The for-profit shift would likely mean the OpenAI CEO Sam Altman would have equity in the company. As far as investing in an AI winner, Keidan says, “We're just still early. And so it's very hard to see what are the competitive advantages and what are going to be the key things that make the winners. And so from that perspective, OpenAI is doing a phenomenal job, but it still remains to be seen across the board. And with Microsoft (MSFT) and Google having other bases of operations that they can play from, [it could] potentially be a challenge.” Keidan says that, as a venture investor, he’s probably more excited about AI than he was a year ago. “The capabilities and the adoption are through the roof, and it's going to absolutely be a moment much like in the 2010s when we saw mobile, social, cloud, and location converge. And that created the DoorDashes (DASH) and Ubers (UBER) and Airbnbs (ABNB).” “The potential is tremendous. I'm more excited than ever. In terms of where it's being hashed out now with these huge companies, infrastructure very early in the curve,” but Keidan says “We're trying to stay out of that, and we're really looking for the commercial application layers, early stage investors and I still think it's early. And on the consumer side, it hasn't been proven out yet, but it will be.” He adds that AI is already improving efficiency within Torch Capital’s start-ups. Keidan notes that he doesn’t expect to see private AI companies announcing initial public offerings anytime soon. “These companies have raised a lot of money. They don't want to be distracted by an IPO. And they're building, and they're growing. I think they're going to sit out another year or maybe two until the markets are wide open. Why create friction when they don't need to?” For more expert insight and the latest market action, click here to watch this full episode of Asking for a Trend.
